In the 3.1.3-alpha release on Nuget for the MonoGame.Binaries, it appears to no longer be possible to set the initial window position. 

I used to be able to do something like this:

var screen = Screen.AllScreens.First(e => e.Primary);
Window.IsBorderless = true;
Window.Position = new Point(screen.Bounds.X, screen.Bounds.Y);
graphics.PreferredBackBufferWidth = screen.Bounds.Width;
graphics.PreferredBackBufferHeight = screen.Bounds.Height;

...but now the Window.Position option is no longer available to me. If I set the PreferredBackBufferWidth/Height to anything other than the default, it puts the window into the bottom right corner in an extremely awkward position and I can't find any way to move this programmatically. Any suggestions? By the way, I would obviously prefer to just have an actual FullScreenMode, but this appears to not be working also.

This is a link to a discussion about this original issue:
https://github.com/mono/MonoGame/issues/1672

this.ScreenValue = new Point(1920, 1200);
        graphics.PreferredBackBufferWidth = this.ScreenValue.X;
        graphics.PreferredBackBufferHeight = this.ScreenValue.Y;
        graphics.IsFullScreen = true;
        graphics.ApplyChanges();

This code works perfectly in XNA but in monogame, the viewport always remains windowed. I have tried various resolutions and it incorrectly sets the size of the window

I'm developing a simple game for android at the moment.
When first starting the game, the colors are all fine and everything looks alright.
If I press the home button and then return to back to the game. All textures are black.

I'm drawing some text on the screen which is still blue when i come back. 
So it's either a problem with my code, or something weird with Texture2D

this is how i load the font

``` csharp
font = Content.Load<SpriteFont>("spriteFont1");
```

this is how i load the texture:

``` csharp
        Texture2D sky = Globals.FilledRectangle(Color.Cyan, this.GraphicsDevice, new Vector2(SCREEN_WIDTH * scale.X, 100 * scale.Y));

        public static Texture2D FilledRectangle(Color color, GraphicsDevice gD, Vector2 size)
        {
            Color[] data = new Color[(int)size.X * (int)size.Y];
            Texture2D temp = new Texture2D(gD, (int)size.X, (int)size.Y);
            for (int count = 0; count < data.Length; count++)
            {
                data[count] = color;
            }
            temp.SetData(data);
            return temp;
        }
```

I'm not 100% sure of this, so I would like to know others opinions...

I'm creating a few RenderTarget2D and some of them are using DepthFormat.None. Following the code I've found this:

```
            // If we don't need a depth buffer then we're done.
            if (preferredDepthFormat == DepthFormat.None)
                return;
```

on the RenderTarget2D's constructor.

glDepthBuffer is zero if there is no need for a depth buffer. That is working flawlessly.
The problem I've found is that when the disposal happens, it does not check if glDepthBuffer is zero or not before deleting it, so I'm getting GL_INVALID_VALUE exception error on the next CheckGLError.
I've came up with this simple solution, surrounding this (inside Dispose method):

```
                    GL.DeleteRenderbuffers(1, ref this.glDepthBuffer);
                    GraphicsExtensions.CheckGLError();
```

with a simple if, like this:

```
                    if (this.glDepthBuffer != 0)
                    {
                        GL.DeleteRenderbuffers(1, ref this.glDepthBuffer);
                        GraphicsExtensions.CheckGLError();
                    }
```

Is this going to break anything or I can submit the PR?
